      "text": "The trouble is that since deregulation, stock values are decoupled from the true value of companies.  Many companies made more money out of trading their stocks than of actual production.  Companies are no longer committed to their product, not even committed to their customers, but only committed to their shareholders; and in this environment, those shareholders expect to get ever increasing returns on their investments, or else they take their money elsewhere."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4d183a0691310dbb",
      "text": "The result is that IBM is no longer a computer company, and Ford is no longer a car company; both are stock traders who use computers or cars as an excuse.  It's difficult to make any improvement on production (or produce anything at all) in such an environment."
